data.content:
Your code **doesn't actually use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses:

- `Thread.Start()` / `Thread.Join()` / `Thread.Sleep()` — these all work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, the code could be modernized to use `Task`-based parallelism, which is idiomatic in modern .NET:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Summary:** No Thread.Abort migration needed here — your code is already compatible with .NET 8 as-is.
